# Maderable Dashboard - AI Assistant Rules

You are working on the Maderable admin dashboard: a React 19 + TypeScript single-page app
built on CoreUI React components, Vite, React Router, TanStack React Query (server state),
Zustand (UI state), and Sass. The codebase follows a **vertical-slice architecture** organized
by feature, and is **fully TypeScript in strict mode**.

## Critical Rules

**Component Library**: ALWAYS use CoreUI React components (https://coreui.io/react/docs/).
NEVER use Tailwind CSS, Material-UI, or other component/CSS libraries. This project is built on
Bootstrap 5 + CoreUI React exclusively.

**Language**: ALL source is TypeScript (`.ts` / `.tsx`). NEVER add `.js`/`.jsx` files under `src/`.
`tsconfig.json` has `strict: true` and ESLint forbids `any` (`@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any: error`).

**No PropTypes**: Type component props with a TypeScript `interface`, not `prop-types`
(the `prop-types` package has been removed).

## Technology Stack

- React 19 — functional components and Hooks only
- TypeScript (strict) — `.tsx` for components, `.ts` for logic/types
- CoreUI React 5.x and @coreui/coreui 5.x
- React Router 7.x (`HashRouter`) for routing
- TanStack React Query 5.x for server state (data fetching/mutations)
- Zustand for local UI state (`src/shared/store/uiStore.ts`: sidebar, theme)
- Vite for dev server and build
- Sass/SCSS with Bootstrap 5 + CoreUI variables
- Chart.js 4.x with @coreui/react-chartjs for visualization

## Architecture: Vertical Slice

Code is organized **by feature**, not by technical layer. Each feature is self-contained under
`src/features/<name>/` and exposes its routes and nav for composition.

```
src/
├── App.tsx                        # Root: HashRouter + public routes + DefaultLayout
├── index.tsx                      # Entry: QueryClientProvider
├── shared/
│   ├── api/
│   │   ├── httpClient.ts          # Typed fetch wrapper: get<T>/list<T>/post<T>/put/patch/delete
│   │   └── types.ts               # Transport types: PaginatedResult<T>, Pagination, ApiError
│   ├── components/                # App shell (AppHeader, AppSidebar, AppContent, …)
│   ├── layout/DefaultLayout.tsx
│   ├── routes.ts                  # AppRoute[] composed from all features
│   └── store/uiStore.ts           # Zustand store
└── features/
    ├── dashboard/  orders/  products/  clients/  review/  auth/  widgets/
    └── <feature>/
        ├── <Feature>Page.tsx      # Page + sub-components (.tsx)
        ├── routes.ts              # export const <feature>Routes: AppRoute[]
        ├── nav.tsx                # export const <feature>Nav: NavItem[]  (JSX → .tsx)
        ├── <feature>Api.ts        # uses shared httpClient with typed generics
        ├── use<Feature>.ts        # React Query hooks (useQuery / useMutation)
        └── types.ts               # co-located domain types/interfaces
```

**To add a feature**: create `src/features/<name>/` with the files above, then wire it in with two
imports — routes into `src/shared/components/AppContent.tsx`, nav into `AppSidebar.tsx`. No other files change.

## Code Conventions

- Functional components with Hooks; prefer `const Component = () => { }`.
- Do NOT `import React` — the project uses the `react-jsx` runtime. Import named hooks/types
  directly: `import { useState, type ChangeEvent } from 'react'`.
- Type props with an `interface`; destructure in the signature:
  `const MyComponent = ({ title }: MyComponentProps) => { … }`.
- Co-locate domain types in the feature's `types.ts`; import with `import type { … }`.
- Server data goes through React Query hooks (`use<Feature>`), never raw `fetch` in components.
- API modules call the shared `httpClient` with explicit generics: `httpClient.get<Order>(…)`.
- Follow React Hooks rules; keep render pure (no `Math.random`/side effects during render).
- Prettier: no semicolons, single quotes, 2-space indentation. Run `npm run lint` before committing.
- `nav.*` files contain JSX (CIcon) → MUST be `.tsx` (Vite only processes JSX in `.tsx`).

## Component Template

```tsx
import { CCard, CCardBody, CCardHeader } from '@coreui/react'
import type { ReactNode } from 'react'

interface MyComponentProps {
  title: string
  children?: ReactNode
}

const MyComponent = ({ title, children }: MyComponentProps) => (
  <CCard>
    <CCardHeader>{title}</CCardHeader>
    <CCardBody>{children}</CCardBody>
  </CCard>
)

export default MyComponent
```

## React Query Hook Template

```ts
import { useMutation, useQuery, useQueryClient } from '@tanstack/react-query'
import { ordersApi } from './ordersApi'

export const useOrders = (params?: OrderListParams) =>
  useQuery({ queryKey: ['orders', params], queryFn: () => ordersApi.list(params) })

export const useCreateOrder = () => {
  const qc = useQueryClient()
  return useMutation({
    mutationFn: ordersApi.create,
    onSuccess: () => qc.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['orders'] }),
  })
}
```

To read `.status`/`.errors` off a query/mutation error, narrow with `error instanceof ApiError`
(`import { ApiError } from 'src/shared/api/types'`) — React Query types errors as `Error` by default.

## Naming Conventions

- PascalCase for component files and components (`AppHeader.tsx`, `DefaultLayout.tsx`).
- camelCase for variables, functions, hooks; UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for module constants.
- kebab-case for CSS classes (Bootstrap/CoreUI conventions).

## Development Workflow

```bash
npm install
npm start            # dev server
npm run build        # production build (vite)
npm run typecheck    # tsc --noEmit (strict)
npm run lint         # eslint src
```

Before committing, the change must pass `npm run typecheck`, `npm run lint`, and `npm run build`.

## Git Commits

Conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:`, `style:`, `refactor:`, `test:`, `chore:`.

## AI Assistant Guidelines

**Do**: use CoreUI React components; write strict TypeScript with typed props (interfaces);
use functional components + Hooks; fetch via React Query hooks + shared `httpClient`; follow the
vertical-slice layout; keep light/dark themes and responsiveness working.

**Don't**: use `any` or `prop-types`; add `.js`/`.jsx` under `src/`; `import React`; use class
components or deprecated patterns; import non-CoreUI UI/CSS libraries; introduce Redux (UI state is
Zustand, server state is React Query); put files outside the feature/shared structure.

